[3] New York (Suffolk County) game birds
Date: Sat 2 Apr 2022
Source: East Hampton Star [edited]
https://www.easthamptonstar.com/villages/202242/bird-flu-outbreak-devastates-flock-sag-harbor


A strain of avian flu state officials have deemed "highly pathogenic" has arrived on the South Fork, where a farm in Sag Harbor lost a flock of about 6000 game birds on [23 Mar 2022] due to the infection and its potential to spread.

The Sag Harbor outbreak, at Spring Farm on Clay Pit Road, was one of 3 discovered in Suffolk County and a total of 6 statewide. In February [2022], 8 birds in a residential backyard flock were euthanized, and on [25 Mar 2022] the virus was detected in a flock of several hundred. Both the State Department of Agriculture and the Suffolk County Health Department declined to specify the locations of the 1st and 3rd outbreaks, but the owner of the 82 year old Spring Farm, confirmed on [Fri 1 Apr 2022] that his flock -- mostly pheasants and ducks raised for sport hunting -- was completely devastated. "It no doubt came from a couple of wild ducks coming into my pond," he said by phone. "I think I'm going to go out of business, probably, but I'm old enough to retire. It's just about that time. This, I think, is the deciding factor."

Dr Joy Bennett, the chief veterinarian with New York State's Department of Agriculture and Markets, said in an interview on [Fri 1 Apr 2022] that there is no risk this strain of avian flu can spread to humans, but the risk to chickens, turkeys, ducks, and other fowl is severe. Sick birds and their eggs do not reach the market for consumers. "This year [2022], it is very worrisome for our poultry flocks because it's a very virulent strain," she said. "It's nothing we've really seen before. This year in particular is really the time poultry producers should be looking or the signs and taking preventative measures."

Those actions, Dr Bennett said, include keeping birds inside whenever possible so they don't encounter the wild birds carrying the virus. People should not feed wild birds like ducks, geese, and even songbirds. Visitors to farms or people's backyards should be limited or prohibited, and those who work directly with poultry should wash their hands and disinfect their boots and tools frequently. Food should be stored securely, she said, "so they don't attract wild birds or rodents. Rodents may not get infected, but they can carry the virus on their feet or fur."

Commissioner Richard Ball of the State Department of Agriculture and Markets described this as an unusual situation, but one threatening poultry farms across New York and 17 other states as well. On [25 Mar 2022] he banned live fowl shows and swaps as a precaution. It's the biggest concern since a major outbreak of avian flu in 2015 in the Midwestern United States, he said. That outbreak claimed the lives of 50 million birds and was caused by wild bird migration. At that time, transportation of poultry from the Midwest was banned.

"We've got a flyway in the Midwest, and a pretty significant one on the East Coast. This is how we're coming to find it in New York State this year," Mr Ball said. "We're reacting very quickly and doing lots of testing to hopefully minimize it. It's as random as a duck or goose or wild fowl getting into the wrong areas." In the February [2022] incident in Suffolk, he said, "The people with the flock had been feeding the wild birds flying through."

Dr Bennett said signs of the avian flu in sick birds include swimming in circles and "twisted" necks. She advised people to report possible infections by phone or by email to <dai@agrcilutre.ny.gov>. "We have a field staff spread out throughout the state -- a very robust staff to address this," she said.

[byline: Christine Sampson]

