[Avian influenza continues its winged flight across North America. Most wild bird species, as well as poultry and other domestic birds, are neither tolerant nor resistant to HPAI viruses, and thus they become ill and do not move much, which implies they are poor spreaders and instead they may act as sentinels of viral circulation. Consequently, please be on alert for the least sign of a bird not feeling well or not eating. Early detection can help limit losses.

Biosecurity of your birds is paramount in keeping them healthy. Just as flu flies, it can also be tracked around on dirty boots or coveralls, and even carried in your own nose without affecting you. Please remember to blow your nose, and put on a clean coverall and boots before entering a poultry facility, regardless of size. If your operation is small enough or you have adequate facilities, move your birds indoors. Be on the lookout for wild birds mingling with your birds. If a bird is not eating, seems a little more listless, or separates itself from the others, then be sure to have your animals checked by a veterinarian immediately. Isolate sick birds. - Mod.TG

